# Copy to .env and uncomment what you need:
#   cp .env.example .env
#
# Identity: set at least ONE provider below for sign-in (required in production).
# Signaling: no .env needed for defaults — both dev and build use public Nostr relays:
#   npm run dev        -> public Nostr relays
#   npm run build      -> public Nostr relays
#   npm run dev:relay  -> local ws-relay instead (offline work)

# --- TURN (optional but recommended for real deployments) ---
# Without TURN, peers behind symmetric NAT / CGNAT / strict firewalls exchange
# signaling and then fail to connect. TURN relays that traffic (still E2E
# encrypted). No default: it costs real bandwidth, so bring your own.
# Conventional 3478/5349 endpoints are automatically expanded to UDP, TCP,
# TLS/5349, and TLS/443. The TURN server must actually expose those listeners.
# VITE_TURN_URLS=turn:your-turn.example:3478,turns:your-turn.example:5349
# Credentials are minted at runtime by /api/network/credentials. Never add a
# long-lived TURN username or credential to a VITE_* variable.

# --- Overrides ---

# Option A: Nostr (the default). Only set this to pin your own relays; the
# built-in defaults are public and may come and go.
# VITE_SIGNALING=nostr
# VITE_NOSTR_RELAYS=wss://nos.lol,wss://relay.damus.io

# Option B: Supabase Realtime (free tier) — a relay you control.
# VITE_SIGNALING=supabase
# VITE_SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project.supabase.co
# VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your-anon-key

# Option C: Self-hosted WebSocket relay
# VITE_SIGNALING=ws-relay
# VITE_RELAY_PORT=8080
#
# VITE_RELAY_HOSTS is a comma-separated failover list. VITE_RELAY_HOST remains
# supported for single-endpoint deployments. Remote relays require tickets.
# Set together with a matching VITE_RELAY_PORT (443 for wss). Authentication
# uses short-lived OIDC/device-bound tickets from the Worker.
# VITE_RELAY_HOSTS=relay-eu.peerly.cc,relay-us.peerly.cc
# VITE_RELAY_PORT=443

# --- Identity (at least one provider required) ---
# Workspace access is decided by the email on a verified ID token, so a provider
# is only safe here if it actually verifies the address it asserts.
# VITE_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=123.apps.googleusercontent.com
# Optional stable Google auth origin for per-branch previews. When omitted,
# Peerly uses its regular direct Google sign-in flow.
# VITE_GOOGLE_AUTH_BRIDGE_ORIGIN=https://your-preview-auth.example.com

# Microsoft: TWO requirements, both enforced.
#  1. VITE_MICROSOFT_TENANT_ID must be a specific tenant (a directory GUID).
#     "common"/"organizations"/"consumers" are refused at startup: Azure lets a
#     tenant admin set an account's email to any unverified value, so a
#     multi-tenant setup lets anyone create a free tenant, assert a member's
#     address, and be admitted ("nOAuth"). One pinned tenant means only your own
#     admins can make that assertion.
#  2. In the app registration, add BOTH optional claims to the ID token:
#     `email` and `xms_edov`. Azure never sends the standard `email_verified`;
#     `xms_edov` is its equivalent, and without it no Microsoft user can join.
# VITE_MICROSOFT_CLIENT_ID=your-azure-app-client-id
# VITE_MICROSOFT_TENANT_ID=11111111-2222-3333-4444-555555555555
# VITE_APPLE_CLIENT_ID=com.example.app.service          # Apple Services ID
# VITE_APPLE_REDIRECT_URI=https://your-domain.com       # optional; defaults to window.location.origin
# VITE_OIDC_CLIENT_ID=your-oidc-client-id
# VITE_OIDC_ISSUER=https://your-idp.example.com
# VITE_OIDC_LABEL=Company SSO

# E2E test ports (server/test-server.mjs)
# TEST_APP_PORT=17273
# TEST_RELAY_PORT=17274
# --- E2E only: NEVER set this for a real build ---
# VITE_E2E_AUTH_BYPASS=true swaps in a fake identity provider whose RSA signing
# key is committed to this repo, so anyone could mint a token for any email and
# join any workspace. It exists so the E2E suite can test the real handshake
# without live Google accounts, and `npm run build` runs `guard:bundle` to fail
# if that key ever reaches a bundle. Set it only in server/test-server.mjs.
# VITE_E2E_AUTH_BYPASS=true
